        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Not necessarily"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Not necessarily<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~cultiv8" class="author" title="author name and user ID">cultiv8 (1660093) </a> | about a year and a half ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3272951&cid=42090123">(#42090123)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_42090123" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body">If you believe the <a href="https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Mining_hardware_comparison" title="bitcoin.it">mhash/s speeds of (yet to be released) ASIC hardware</a> <span class="domain-text"> [bitcoin.it]</span> , as well as <a href="https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/P2Pool" title="bitcoin.it">decentralized P2Pool mining</a> <span class="domain-text"> [bitcoin.it]</span> , then you'll need to factor in the effect of disruptive technologies on "deflationary spirals". Bitcoin mining was something I was recently evaluating and decided against after <a href="http://bitcoinx.com/profit/index.php" title="bitcoinx.com">researching</a> <span class="domain-text"> [bitcoinx.com]</span>  and factoring in the effects of profitability decline per year on revenue, especially if ASIC hardware delivers as specced.</div>
