    <div id="comment_42090357">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:only ever be 21,000,000 bitcoins"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:only ever be 21,000,000 bitcoins<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~joelpt" class="author" title="author name and user ID">joelpt (21056) </a> | about a year and a half ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3272951&cid=42090357">(#42090357)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_42090357" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>They are just numbers. Bitcoins could therefore be subdivided as small as is reasonable or required for actual usage. For example, the main Bitcoin client currently allows you to display bitcoin figures in BTC, mBTC (1/1000 BTC), or BTC (1/1000000 BTC).</p><p>I believe the current Bitcoin protocol supports subdivisions up to 8 decimal places. Apparently this can be extended further with minor alterations to the existing Bitcoin protocol.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_42090357">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="3272951" data-cid="42090357">
